WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.590 --> 00:00:04.340
SPEAKER 1: So thank you guys for
joining us for our first Google

00:00:04.340 --> 00:00:08.290
Talks in the Birmingham office.

00:00:08.290 --> 00:00:12.270
I have the great pleasure today
to introduce Bridget Russo,

00:00:12.270 --> 00:00:14.130
the CMO of Shinola.

00:00:14.130 --> 00:00:16.490
Before I do, for
those of you who

00:00:16.490 --> 00:00:20.124
don't have a deep background
on the company itself,

00:00:20.124 --> 00:00:21.540
I wanted to give
you a little bit.

00:00:21.540 --> 00:00:23.250
It was conceived in 2011.

00:00:23.250 --> 00:00:25.160
So when we think
about our own brand,

00:00:25.160 --> 00:00:27.590
Shinola is only
about five years old.

00:00:27.590 --> 00:00:31.070
It is the maker of modern
handcraft watches, bicycles,

00:00:31.070 --> 00:00:34.942
leather goods, journals,
and pet accessories,

00:00:34.942 --> 00:00:36.650
of which it sounds
like they're expanding

00:00:36.650 --> 00:00:38.070
into even more products.

00:00:38.070 --> 00:00:40.300
So we'll hear from
Bridget about that.

00:00:40.300 --> 00:00:42.015
They're really
focused on again, you

00:00:42.015 --> 00:00:43.390
think about those
of you who work

00:00:43.390 --> 00:00:46.330
in the automotive industry,
some of the importance

00:00:46.330 --> 00:00:51.180
of handcrafting, leather,
some of the more upscale ways

00:00:51.180 --> 00:00:55.540
that we try and convey
important elements of our auto

00:00:55.540 --> 00:00:57.270
manufacturers background.

00:00:57.270 --> 00:00:59.650
A lot of that is in the
messages that Shinola

00:00:59.650 --> 00:01:00.720
brings into the market.

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:03.680
So really interesting there.

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:06.910
As far as their locations,
those of you probably know,

00:01:06.910 --> 00:01:09.730
they're headquartered here
in Detroit in the College

00:01:09.730 --> 00:01:11.650
for Creative Studies
building, which

00:01:11.650 --> 00:01:16.110
was a former automotive
research lab.

00:01:16.110 --> 00:01:18.200
And then since the
company's founding,

00:01:18.200 --> 00:01:21.400
they have I think
about seven stores now

00:01:21.400 --> 00:01:23.160
that they've opened up.

00:01:23.160 --> 00:01:25.730
As Bridget herself, a little
bit of background on Bridget.

00:01:25.730 --> 00:01:29.270
Her background started in
PR, which is coming in handy.

00:01:29.270 --> 00:01:31.830
Obviously as a CMO, you have
to deal with a lot of things,

00:01:31.830 --> 00:01:34.490
particularly in
social media nowadays.

00:01:34.490 --> 00:01:37.130
With her background in PR, she
started on the agency side--

00:01:37.130 --> 00:01:39.650
very familiar to some of
you-- and then moved over

00:01:39.650 --> 00:01:43.330
onto the client side, working
with Diesel in the fashion

00:01:43.330 --> 00:01:44.430
industry.

00:01:44.430 --> 00:01:47.250
From there she moved
and started to work

00:01:47.250 --> 00:01:52.900
with Eden, which is a company
that Bono started with his wife

00:01:52.900 --> 00:01:57.760
to support some of the-- to
drive industry in Africa.

00:01:57.760 --> 00:02:00.260
And that moved her into
her own consultancy,

00:02:00.260 --> 00:02:02.950
which a lot of
our Googlers do is

00:02:02.950 --> 00:02:04.200
to start their own businesses.

00:02:04.200 --> 00:02:08.520
And from there it led her
to Shinola and from New York

00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:09.419
to Detroit.

00:02:09.419 --> 00:02:13.440
And so with that, we welcome
her and want to hear her story

00:02:13.440 --> 00:02:15.510
and learn a bit
more about Shinola.

00:02:15.510 --> 00:02:17.060
So with that, I'll
welcome Bridget.

00:02:17.060 --> 00:02:19.305
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:25.261 --> 00:02:27.760
BRIDGET RUSSO: Thank you for
taking the time out of your day

00:02:27.760 --> 00:02:30.860
to hear the Shinola story.

00:02:30.860 --> 00:02:32.628
Can everybody hear me OK?

00:02:32.628 --> 00:02:33.128
OK.

00:02:33.128 --> 00:02:34.100
Cool.

00:02:34.100 --> 00:02:35.880
So I'm going to take
you through quickly,

00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:37.749
since we do have the
fireside chat, and I do

00:02:37.749 --> 00:02:39.290
want to give you
guys the opportunity

00:02:39.290 --> 00:02:40.660
to ask questions afterwards.

00:02:40.660 --> 00:02:43.200
So I'll kind of whiz
through this a little bit,

00:02:43.200 --> 00:02:46.270
give you a little background as
to why we started the company,

00:02:46.270 --> 00:02:50.290
and what's up next in
terms of new categories.

00:02:50.290 --> 00:02:53.230
So we started with building
a watch factory in Detroit.

00:02:53.230 --> 00:02:56.530
Back in 2011, people thought
our founder, Tom Kartsotis,

00:02:56.530 --> 00:02:58.140
was crazy.

00:02:58.140 --> 00:02:59.600
Why not accept
that manufacturing

00:02:59.600 --> 00:03:00.850
is gone from this country?

00:03:00.850 --> 00:03:03.420
Why not let the rust and weeds
finish what they started?

00:03:03.420 --> 00:03:05.970
Why not just embrace the
era of disposability?

00:03:05.970 --> 00:03:09.711
And why didn't we buy a warmer
coat before we moved here?

00:03:09.711 --> 00:03:11.210
Through three Detroit
winters, we've

00:03:11.210 --> 00:03:13.001
asked ourselves these
questions, and worked

00:03:13.001 --> 00:03:15.590
not to find our answers,
but to build it.

00:03:15.590 --> 00:03:18.210
So really from the
beginning, the intention

00:03:18.210 --> 00:03:21.770
was always to not
only be in a city

00:03:21.770 --> 00:03:25.280
where manufacturing was in its
history and in its lifeblood,

00:03:25.280 --> 00:03:26.740
but also to be in
a city where we

00:03:26.740 --> 00:03:29.050
could have a positive
impact on the community.

00:03:29.050 --> 00:03:32.170
In our case, in creating jobs.

00:03:32.170 --> 00:03:36.230
Here's a little video.

00:03:36.230 --> 00:03:37.730
So this is where it all began.

00:03:37.730 --> 00:03:37.783
