00:03:37.783 --> 00:03:39.616
-The question isn't why
do you build a watch

00:03:39.616 --> 00:03:42.600
factory in Detroit, it's why
you built one anywhere else?

00:03:42.600 --> 00:03:45.170
This is the city that
made this country.

00:03:45.170 --> 00:03:49.280
With its steel, with its
skill, with its labor.

00:03:49.280 --> 00:03:50.880
Re-establishing
trades that haven't

00:03:50.880 --> 00:03:53.690
been seen in this country
in a generation or more.

00:03:53.690 --> 00:03:55.590
It's a tall order
to return to form.

00:03:55.590 --> 00:03:58.000
But it's what hundreds
of Shinola employees

00:03:58.000 --> 00:03:59.846
work towards every
day here in Detroit,

00:03:59.846 --> 00:04:02.410
where we believe in
the beauty of industry,

00:04:02.410 --> 00:04:04.220
the glory of manufacturing.

00:04:04.220 --> 00:04:05.450
Shinola.

00:04:05.450 --> 00:04:06.968
Where American is made.

00:04:06.968 --> 00:04:09.610
[END PLAYBACK]

00:04:09.610 --> 00:04:11.530
BRIDGET RUSSO: So it
started with watches.

00:04:11.530 --> 00:04:15.790
We launched our first
product in 2013.

00:04:15.790 --> 00:04:17.850
The factory opened
in 2012, which

00:04:17.850 --> 00:04:20.019
is when I started
with the company.

00:04:20.019 --> 00:04:23.850
Alongside watches, we also
had bicycles, leather goods,

00:04:23.850 --> 00:04:25.390
and journals.

00:04:25.390 --> 00:04:27.410
But really our messaging
from the beginning

00:04:27.410 --> 00:04:32.060
was watches built in
Detroit of quality.

00:04:32.060 --> 00:04:33.190
And so we started there.

00:04:33.190 --> 00:04:36.618
Our first watch was the Runwell.

00:04:36.618 --> 00:04:39.310
If you guys were
around at that time

00:04:39.310 --> 00:04:42.290
paying attention to
some of the marketing,

00:04:42.290 --> 00:04:44.736
we had launched the Runwell
watch before we actually

00:04:44.736 --> 00:04:45.860
have product in the market.

00:04:45.860 --> 00:04:48.600
So that was March 2013.

00:04:48.600 --> 00:04:50.710
The previous year we
had a brand website up

00:04:50.710 --> 00:04:52.700
where we were speaking
directly to the consumer

00:04:52.700 --> 00:04:56.680
through social-- primarily at
the time Twitter and Facebook--

00:04:56.680 --> 00:04:59.680
and really telling people
about our story directly,

00:04:59.680 --> 00:05:03.650
not going through the trades
and sort of the normal way

00:05:03.650 --> 00:05:04.910
you would launch a brand.

00:05:04.910 --> 00:05:06.770
Showing product before
it was finished,

00:05:06.770 --> 00:05:09.710
selling swatches of leather,
talking about our relationship

00:05:09.710 --> 00:05:12.842
with the College for Creative
Studies, where we're based,

00:05:12.842 --> 00:05:14.800
to the degree that some
people were confused as

00:05:14.800 --> 00:05:15.650
to what we were.

00:05:15.650 --> 00:05:17.680
They would be like, are
you a watch company?

00:05:17.680 --> 00:05:18.860
Are you a bike company?

00:05:18.860 --> 00:05:20.490
Are you a school?

00:05:20.490 --> 00:05:25.210
But that really helped lead us
to the launch of the Runwell.

00:05:25.210 --> 00:05:28.160
Fast forward to March of 2013.

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:32.010
We had about 10,000 people on
our e-mail lists at that point.

00:05:32.010 --> 00:05:34.050
And about the same
number of followers

00:05:34.050 --> 00:05:36.140
on Facebook and Twitter.

00:05:36.140 --> 00:05:37.820
And we launched the watch.

00:05:37.820 --> 00:05:40.470
We hadn't actually
made the watch yet.

00:05:40.470 --> 00:05:42.030
$550 price point.

00:05:42.030 --> 00:05:44.170
We had 2,500 units.

00:05:44.170 --> 00:05:46.380
By the end of that
week, so eight days,

00:05:46.380 --> 00:05:50.066
we sold out of the watch,
which was pretty incredible.

00:05:50.066 --> 00:05:51.690
We really didn't know
in the beginning.

00:05:51.690 --> 00:05:54.370
There was some who thought
that Shinola would actually

00:05:54.370 --> 00:05:57.810
be more of a company to make
watches for other brands.

00:05:57.810 --> 00:05:59.830
But then when we saw the
strength of the Runwell

00:05:59.830 --> 00:06:03.800
in the Shinola brand, we
decided to go full force.

00:06:03.800 --> 00:06:05.590
Subsequently, we've
launched these other

00:06:05.590 --> 00:06:07.170
what we call platforms.

00:06:07.170 --> 00:06:11.390
And most recently the Canfield,
which is a refined Runwell.

00:06:11.390 --> 00:06:12.250
Bicycles.

00:06:12.250 --> 00:06:16.000
So bicycles, going back
to the '80s really,

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:17.370
that production went offshore.

00:06:17.370 --> 00:06:21.040
The US primarily one
of the biggest names,

00:06:21.040 --> 00:06:22.674
Schwinn, you might know.

00:06:22.674 --> 00:06:23.840
The brand's still out there.

00:06:23.840 --> 00:06:25.740
But it's not owned by
the family anymore.

00:06:25.740 --> 00:06:28.710
They were one of the last
to move their manufacturing

00:06:28.710 --> 00:06:29.210
overseas.

00:06:29.210 --> 00:06:32.760
So they lost the right-- or
sold the rights to their name.

00:06:32.760 --> 00:06:35.710
But they did hold onto one
piece of their business,

00:06:35.710 --> 00:06:37.880
called Waterford
Precision Cycles.

00:06:37.880 --> 00:06:40.950
So they were making
custom bicycles, $10,000

00:06:40.950 --> 00:06:44.350
and up, that people
would wait months for.

00:06:44.350 --> 00:06:46.040
So we met Sky Yaeger.

00:06:46.040 --> 00:06:47.810
How we approach all
of our categories

00:06:47.810 --> 00:06:49.925
is really finding leaders
within that category.

00:06:49.925 --> 00:06:53.220
So in the case of
bikes, that was Sky.

00:06:53.220 --> 00:06:55.657
Sky said, I know the
guy we need to go to.

00:06:55.657 --> 00:06:57.240
Richard Schwinn up
there in the corner

00:06:57.240 --> 00:07:00.885
is a great grandson of the man
who started Schwinn bicycles.

00:07:00.885 --> 00:07:02.760
And we approached him
and said, what would it

00:07:02.760 --> 00:07:04.890
take for you to make
bicycles for Shinola?

00:07:04.890 --> 00:07:07.120
And we said we'll probably
make about 1,000 a year.

00:07:07.120 --> 00:07:08.810
He's like, I need
to hire more people.

00:07:08.810 --> 00:07:10.110
So we're like great.

00:07:10.110 --> 00:07:13.291
Right in line with
our messaging.

00:07:13.291 --> 00:07:15.540
So some people ask, well,
why are the bikes so pricey?

00:07:15.540 --> 00:07:18.120
The Runwell is $3,000.

00:07:18.120 --> 00:07:20.720
The Bixby that you
see there is $2,000.

00:07:20.720 --> 00:07:23.500
And it's because of the
quality and the craftsmanship

00:07:23.500 --> 00:07:25.400
that goes into it.

00:07:25.400 --> 00:07:28.470
So we make the frame
and fork with Waterford.

00:07:28.470 --> 00:07:30.900
And then we assemble the
bikes, as you see there,

00:07:30.900 --> 00:07:31.880
in our Detroit store.

00:07:33.380 --> 00:07:33.880
Paper.

00:07:33.880 --> 00:07:40.630
We work with a bindery in Ann
Arbor, or close to Ann Arbor,

00:07:40.630 --> 00:07:43.335
called Malloy Brothers.

00:07:43.335 --> 00:07:45.840
Sorry, I had a brain
fart there for a minute.

00:07:45.840 --> 00:07:48.134
And again, we really
saw the market.

00:07:48.134 --> 00:07:49.800
So with all of our
categories, we really

00:07:49.800 --> 00:07:54.160
look at them in two
ways-- as brand builders

00:07:54.160 --> 00:07:55.860
or as volume drivers.

00:07:55.860 --> 00:07:58.470
So bicycles, leather,
and soon to be

00:07:58.470 --> 00:08:00.940
audio, which I'll tell
you about in a little bit,

00:08:00.940 --> 00:08:02.680
are really the volume drivers.

00:08:02.680 --> 00:08:06.700
And things like the journals,
bicycles, pet accessories,

00:08:06.700 --> 00:08:08.180
are the brand builders.

00:08:08.180 --> 00:08:09.630
They're equally as important.

00:08:09.630 --> 00:08:14.620
But it really helps us
not only kind of continue

00:08:14.620 --> 00:08:17.570
to provide products that are
relevant to the lifestyle

00:08:17.570 --> 00:08:20.510
of our consumer, but also
to add a point of difference

00:08:20.510 --> 00:08:21.340
in the marketplace.

00:08:21.340 --> 00:08:23.770
So if you go into a
Neiman's or a Nordstrom

00:08:23.770 --> 00:08:26.650
in the watch department you
might see a Shinola bike

00:08:26.650 --> 00:08:28.270
hanging.

00:08:28.270 --> 00:08:30.940
We actually made all of the
buyers of the big department

00:08:30.940 --> 00:08:34.539
stores come to Detroit before
they wanted to buy the line.

00:08:34.539 --> 00:08:38.130
So that definitely
was helpful in helping

00:08:38.130 --> 00:08:42.110
them show the full breadth
of the brand in their stores.

00:08:42.110 --> 00:08:42.850
Leather.

00:08:42.850 --> 00:08:46.080
We recently signed on
a few years ago now.

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:47.300
John and Richard.

00:08:47.300 --> 00:08:49.570
They had a brand called
Lambertson and Truex

00:08:49.570 --> 00:08:51.140
that did very well.

00:08:51.140 --> 00:08:53.647
They're highly regarded
in the fashion industry.

00:08:53.647 --> 00:08:56.230
Then they moved on to Tiffany's
where they built their leather

00:08:56.230 --> 00:08:58.830
business to a $50
million business,

00:08:58.830 --> 00:09:00.850
and were kind of
in semi-retirement

00:09:00.850 --> 00:09:03.300
when we approached them to
run our leather business.

00:09:03.300 --> 00:09:05.210
So we started with a
small leather goods,

00:09:05.210 --> 00:09:09.340
and have expanded now
into bags, wallets, belts.

00:09:09.340 --> 00:09:11.920
Come this fall, we'll really
have a full representation

00:09:11.920 --> 00:09:13.930
for women.

00:09:13.930 --> 00:09:17.290
So again, looking at leaders
within the categories

00:09:17.290 --> 00:09:19.410
to lead the design
and production.

00:09:22.360 --> 00:09:23.540
And then pet accessories.

00:09:23.540 --> 00:09:25.610
So these are these
fun categories.

00:09:25.610 --> 00:09:28.970
Just as much work, but
ones that really help

00:09:28.970 --> 00:09:30.410
create the buzz
around the brand.

00:09:30.410 --> 00:09:31.868
Because it's not
every day that you

00:09:31.868 --> 00:09:33.860
launch a new watch
or a new bicycle

00:09:33.860 --> 00:09:36.660
or a new range of journals.

00:09:36.660 --> 00:09:42.372
But this is an opportunity to
get that PR earned media value.

00:09:42.372 --> 00:09:43.330
And then the marketing.

00:09:43.330 --> 00:09:45.230
So it all started--
this was the ad that we

00:09:45.230 --> 00:09:49.470
ran going back in March 2013.

00:09:49.470 --> 00:09:51.170
At first we weren't
going to advertise.

00:09:51.170 --> 00:09:51.820
We're like, no.

00:09:51.820 --> 00:09:53.028
We're not that kind of brand.

00:09:53.028 --> 00:09:55.780
We're not going to do it.

00:09:55.780 --> 00:09:57.500
Right about when
I came on board,

00:09:57.500 --> 00:09:59.800
we hired an agency called
Partners and Spade, based out

00:09:59.800 --> 00:10:00.430
of New York.

00:10:00.430 --> 00:10:05.130
They really helped us design the
next version of the site, which

00:10:05.130 --> 00:10:07.690
is pretty much
what you see today,

00:10:07.690 --> 00:10:09.410
and really put a
stake in the ground

00:10:09.410 --> 00:10:14.950
around Detroit-built
watches of quality.

00:10:14.950 --> 00:10:17.210
And we decided to
take this ad out.

00:10:17.210 --> 00:10:20.190
We ran it in the "New York
Times," "USA Today," "Detroit

00:10:20.190 --> 00:10:23.780
Free Press," in the "Wall
Street Journal" sort of mid week

00:10:23.780 --> 00:10:25.790
in the process of
selling the watch

00:10:25.790 --> 00:10:28.820
and by the time the "New York
Times," Sunday Times style,

00:10:28.820 --> 00:10:29.726
ran on Sunday.

00:10:29.726 --> 00:10:30.850
They were sold out already.

00:10:33.640 --> 00:10:34.640
You might remember this.

00:10:34.640 --> 00:10:36.270
When Detroit
announced bankruptcy,

00:10:36.270 --> 00:10:39.765
a few days later, we ran
this in the "New York Times."

00:10:39.765 --> 00:10:41.390
"To those who have
written off Detroit,

00:10:41.390 --> 00:10:42.575
we give you the Birdie."

00:10:42.575 --> 00:10:44.670
The Birdie happened to
be a watch that we were

00:10:44.670 --> 00:10:46.340
releasing at the same time.

00:10:46.340 --> 00:10:50.840
And again, the PR value
on this was amazing.

00:10:50.840 --> 00:10:54.260
And again, you know
for me, if you guys

00:10:54.260 --> 00:10:56.250
are familiar with PR
Newswire, that's where you

00:10:56.250 --> 00:10:58.710
would put your press releases.

00:10:58.710 --> 00:11:01.910
I really saw the "New York
Times" as our PR Newswire.

00:11:01.910 --> 00:11:04.090
I found that when you had
something relevant that

00:11:04.090 --> 00:11:08.250
had culturally relevant
impact, the "New York Times"

00:11:08.250 --> 00:11:09.690
was a great vehicle.

00:11:09.690 --> 00:11:11.920
When it came to Mothers
Day and Fathers Day,

00:11:11.920 --> 00:11:14.660
and we were just announcing the
Runwell in a different color,

00:11:14.660 --> 00:11:16.590
that was probably
not the best ROI

00:11:16.590 --> 00:11:19.964
to run a full page ad
in the "New York Times."

00:11:19.964 --> 00:11:22.130
And then the second year
we worked with Bruce Weber.

00:11:22.130 --> 00:11:23.930
So Bruce Weber, you
guys might know,

00:11:23.930 --> 00:11:26.960
the famed fashion photographer.

00:11:26.960 --> 00:11:29.200
I like to say the first
year we showed people

00:11:29.200 --> 00:11:32.120
what was behind our doors,
highlighting the people that

00:11:32.120 --> 00:11:34.270
work in the factory and
establishing ourselves

00:11:34.270 --> 00:11:36.420
as a leader within the industry.

00:11:36.420 --> 00:11:40.070
And then the next year with
our work with Bruce, really

00:11:40.070 --> 00:11:42.280
is a love letter to Detroit,
celebrating the people

00:11:42.280 --> 00:11:43.860
outside of our doors,
and why we came

00:11:43.860 --> 00:11:47.760
to Detroit in the first place.

00:11:47.760 --> 00:11:50.090
Last year you might
remember the launch

00:11:50.090 --> 00:11:53.060
in April of the Apple Watch.

00:11:53.060 --> 00:11:56.820
We called the agency I think
a week before and said, hey,

00:11:56.820 --> 00:11:58.310
can you guys come
up with something

00:11:58.310 --> 00:12:02.140
that would kind of just
get us in the conversation

00:12:02.140 --> 00:12:03.700
of this major launch?

00:12:03.700 --> 00:12:05.267
And so they came up with this.

00:12:05.267 --> 00:12:06.850
"A watch so smart
that it can tell you

00:12:06.850 --> 00:12:08.410
the time just by looking at it.

00:12:08.410 --> 00:12:08.940
Runwell.

00:12:08.940 --> 00:12:11.130
Just smart enough."

00:12:11.130 --> 00:12:13.905
So we ran these ads,
again, sprinkle here

00:12:13.905 --> 00:12:16.030
and there. "Wall Street
Journal," "New York Times,"

00:12:16.030 --> 00:12:17.490
ran some digital around it too.

00:12:17.490 --> 00:12:19.960
And again, the buzz that
we created off of it

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:22.230
was really tremendous.

00:12:22.230 --> 00:12:24.460
In a time when-- and
we all know how much

00:12:24.460 --> 00:12:26.030
Apple spends on advertising.

00:12:26.030 --> 00:12:28.210
So had a few friends
that work there.

00:12:28.210 --> 00:12:31.050
And I got a text from
one saying, cheeky.

00:12:31.050 --> 00:12:33.600
Which it was.

00:12:33.600 --> 00:12:35.330
And then this year.

00:12:35.330 --> 00:12:36.940
In an election
year, we knew jobs

00:12:36.940 --> 00:12:39.290
was going to be a hot topic.

00:12:39.290 --> 00:12:41.150
And we really wanted
to celebrate the fact

00:12:41.150 --> 00:12:44.150
that we created over 500
jobs since we launched.

00:12:44.150 --> 00:12:45.860
And so we came out
with this campaign.

00:12:45.860 --> 00:12:47.450
"There's a funny thing
that happens when you build

00:12:47.450 --> 00:12:48.650
factories in this country.

00:12:48.650 --> 00:12:49.850
It's called jobs."

00:12:49.850 --> 00:12:54.160
And again, really highlighting
the people behind the products.

00:12:54.160 --> 00:12:55.661
We are a true
manufacturing company

00:12:55.661 --> 00:12:57.910
built not by the things we
make, but by the people who

00:12:57.910 --> 00:13:00.010
make them.

00:13:00.010 --> 00:13:05.130
This year in the past, we were
primarily-- our media plan

00:13:05.130 --> 00:13:06.600
was primarily print.

00:13:06.600 --> 00:13:08.880
And we started to see
some diminishing returns

00:13:08.880 --> 00:13:11.230
I would say, mid-last year.

00:13:11.230 --> 00:13:13.680
So we really did a shift
towards digital this year,

00:13:13.680 --> 00:13:16.350
working with premium partners
like "Vanity Fair," "Elle,"

00:13:16.350 --> 00:13:19.880
"Harper's Bazaar,"
"Vice," to create content.

00:13:19.880 --> 00:13:22.730
So some of that you
guys might have seen.

00:13:22.730 --> 00:13:25.150
We'll continue with that
for second half of the year

00:13:25.150 --> 00:13:26.740
around big product launches.

00:13:26.740 --> 00:13:28.890
So continuing to talk
about our leather,

00:13:28.890 --> 00:13:31.450
our watches, and expand
our reach outside

00:13:31.450 --> 00:13:34.560
of our media consumers.

00:13:34.560 --> 00:13:38.710
Our big push for second half of
the year will be around women.

00:13:38.710 --> 00:13:41.520
The challenge that we do have
is that talking about jobs

00:13:41.520 --> 00:13:42.250
is great.

00:13:42.250 --> 00:13:45.960
But when you're trying to sell
a hobo bag, talking about jobs

00:13:45.960 --> 00:13:47.330
doesn't really help.

00:13:47.330 --> 00:13:50.650
It doesn't mean that women
don't care about creating jobs.

00:13:50.650 --> 00:13:54.110
But when you're trying to sell
someone this great leather bag,

00:13:54.110 --> 00:13:56.700
that messaging doesn't
always link up together.

00:13:56.700 --> 00:13:58.616
So that's something that
we're working through

00:13:58.616 --> 00:14:01.400
now to understand
probably around September,

00:14:01.400 --> 00:14:05.181
around the debates, the jobs
messaging will come up again.

00:14:05.181 --> 00:14:06.930
But then we'll make a
shift towards really

00:14:06.930 --> 00:14:09.160
focusing on celebrating
our women's product

00:14:09.160 --> 00:14:13.410
and showing people that we're
serious about our women's

00:14:13.410 --> 00:14:15.620
products.

00:14:15.620 --> 00:14:16.120
Retail.

00:14:16.120 --> 00:14:18.830
So our retail
environments are really,

00:14:18.830 --> 00:14:21.260
in my view, part
of our marketing.

00:14:21.260 --> 00:14:23.740
We look at them as
living, breathing things.

00:14:23.740 --> 00:14:25.910
They're not museums
for products.

00:14:25.910 --> 00:14:27.980
They're really community spaces.

00:14:27.980 --> 00:14:31.930
So we activate our stores quite
frequently, two to three times

00:14:31.930 --> 00:14:33.310
a month.

00:14:33.310 --> 00:14:34.800
We not only throw
our own events,

00:14:34.800 --> 00:14:36.930
but we open them up
to the community.

00:14:36.930 --> 00:14:41.320
So the local PR association
might hold their annual meeting

00:14:41.320 --> 00:14:42.820
in the morning.

00:14:42.820 --> 00:14:46.990
We work with Creative Mornings
to hold talks in our stores.

00:14:46.990 --> 00:14:50.780
We're currently working with
a local barber shop in Detroit

00:14:50.780 --> 00:14:52.430
called The Social Club, too.

00:14:52.430 --> 00:14:56.920
They do a series called Shop
Talk, where they actually cut

00:14:56.920 --> 00:15:00.230
people's hair while they're
participating in a talk.

00:15:00.230 --> 00:15:01.480
It sounds weird, but it works.

00:15:01.480 --> 00:15:04.330
If anybody has attended,
they're pretty interesting.

00:15:04.330 --> 00:15:06.980
So we're doing that not only
in Detroit and Ann Arbor,

00:15:06.980 --> 00:15:08.010
but across cities.

00:15:08.010 --> 00:15:11.480
DC, New York, LA.

00:15:11.480 --> 00:15:14.362
And each store is really unique,
taking on the personality not

00:15:14.362 --> 00:15:15.820
only of the building
that we're in,

00:15:15.820 --> 00:15:19.440
but also the city that we're in.

00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:20.220
And there's a few.

00:15:20.220 --> 00:15:24.380
We're now at is
it 15, 16 stores?

00:15:24.380 --> 00:15:26.440
By the end of this year
we'll have 20, and aim

00:15:26.440 --> 00:15:28.502
to open eight to 10 every year.

00:15:31.250 --> 00:15:32.690
What's next.

00:15:32.690 --> 00:15:33.340
The fun part.

00:15:33.340 --> 00:15:34.490
Audio.

00:15:34.490 --> 00:15:39.040
So come October, November, we'll
start with turntables, working

00:15:39.040 --> 00:15:42.640
with this gentleman here,
Alex Rossen, who again,

00:15:42.640 --> 00:15:44.740
is a leader within the category.

00:15:44.740 --> 00:15:47.470
He started a headphone
brand that he's got on right

00:15:47.470 --> 00:15:49.040
there called Audeze.

00:15:49.040 --> 00:15:50.760
Looks like he has
waffles on his ears.

00:15:50.760 --> 00:15:54.520
But highly regarded within
the audiophile community.

00:15:54.520 --> 00:15:56.050
So again, we saw an opportunity.

00:15:56.050 --> 00:15:59.020
If you look at what
Beats did, Beats

00:15:59.020 --> 00:16:02.180
charges a lot of money for a
product that doesn't really

00:16:02.180 --> 00:16:03.360
warrant that price point.

00:16:03.360 --> 00:16:05.330
And everyone, you walk
around and you see them.

00:16:05.330 --> 00:16:06.788
Sure, a lot of
people in the office

00:16:06.788 --> 00:16:08.460
might have Beats headphones.

00:16:08.460 --> 00:16:10.640
But our audiophile
friends tell us

00:16:10.640 --> 00:16:13.030
that it is not the
quality that it

00:16:13.030 --> 00:16:14.280
should be for the price point.

00:16:14.280 --> 00:16:17.310
So we saw an opportunity
to bring value

00:16:17.310 --> 00:16:23.170
into the category with good
design and audiophile quality.

00:16:23.170 --> 00:16:24.020
And then jewelry.

00:16:24.020 --> 00:16:27.120
So some of you may
recognize Pamela Love.

00:16:27.120 --> 00:16:28.700
She's a designer
out of New York.

00:16:28.700 --> 00:16:31.000
We're partnering
with her to launch

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:33.330
jewelry come mid-October.

00:16:33.330 --> 00:16:36.040
This will be part of a larger
Shinola women's launch.

00:16:36.040 --> 00:16:39.530
So not only jewelry, but
expanding our watch offering

00:16:39.530 --> 00:16:41.760
in a new collection
called Gomelsky.

00:16:41.760 --> 00:16:43.790
We do have a style right
now called Gomelsky.

00:16:43.790 --> 00:16:47.360
But this is sort of
an offshoot of that.

00:16:47.360 --> 00:16:49.740
And this is one of
my favorite films

00:16:49.740 --> 00:16:51.816
that we did with Bruce Weber.

