00:18:57.920 --> 00:19:00.120
And so when you look
at some of this,

00:19:00.120 --> 00:19:02.430
and you can see how
you're investing

00:19:02.430 --> 00:19:06.847
in having the best
people, build the products

00:19:06.847 --> 00:19:07.680
you want to present.

00:19:07.680 --> 00:19:09.180
Can you talk a little
bit about that?

00:19:09.180 --> 00:19:10.013
BRIDGET RUSSO: Yeah.

00:19:10.013 --> 00:19:12.670
So it's a concept
that I was first

00:19:12.670 --> 00:19:15.440
introduced to when
working for Bono and Ali

00:19:15.440 --> 00:19:18.090
back in 2004 when they
launched the brand Eden.

00:19:18.090 --> 00:19:20.090
And they were really
pioneers in the space,

00:19:20.090 --> 00:19:21.710
especially in fashion.

00:19:21.710 --> 00:19:25.190
The idea of conscious fashion.

00:19:25.190 --> 00:19:27.100
People didn't understand.

00:19:27.100 --> 00:19:28.990
The green movement
was happening.

00:19:28.990 --> 00:19:30.790
There was some organic
brands out there.

00:19:30.790 --> 00:19:33.930
None of them were
all that fashionable.

00:19:33.930 --> 00:19:37.980
So this idea that you could
have quality product out there,

00:19:37.980 --> 00:19:41.180
but by the nature of
your business practices,

00:19:41.180 --> 00:19:43.040
your production
practices, you were also

00:19:43.040 --> 00:19:46.420
helping to build communities
and have a positive impact.

00:19:46.420 --> 00:19:48.970
Coming from the fashion
industry, where you never

00:19:48.970 --> 00:19:52.120
talked about your production,
in part because you didn't want

00:19:52.120 --> 00:19:54.790
to let your competitors know
where you were manufacturing,

00:19:54.790 --> 00:19:58.130
but also now we
know so many things

00:19:58.130 --> 00:19:59.184
have happened since then.

00:19:59.184 --> 00:20:00.850
You guys probably
weren't even born yet.

00:20:00.850 --> 00:20:02.060
Kathie Lee Gifford.

00:20:02.060 --> 00:20:02.580
Nike.

00:20:02.580 --> 00:20:06.570
And everything subsequently
that happened from there.

00:20:06.570 --> 00:20:08.030
It wasn't pretty.

00:20:08.030 --> 00:20:12.200
The fashion industry can
be a pretty ugly industry,

00:20:12.200 --> 00:20:14.050
or has been in the past.

00:20:14.050 --> 00:20:14.980
Not intentionally.

00:20:14.980 --> 00:20:18.360
I think as things went offshore,
that control and understanding

00:20:18.360 --> 00:20:21.740
of how things were being
manufactured in other places,

00:20:21.740 --> 00:20:25.310
they weren't up to the
same standards as the US.

00:20:25.310 --> 00:20:28.010
So a lot of people
early on got burned.

00:20:28.010 --> 00:20:30.210
I don't think Nike
set out intentionally

00:20:30.210 --> 00:20:32.580
to have children
making their clothes.

00:20:32.580 --> 00:20:35.730
But unfortunately, it's hard
to have that control when

00:20:35.730 --> 00:20:37.170
you're doing things overseas.

00:20:37.170 --> 00:20:39.140
A lot has changed.

00:20:39.140 --> 00:20:43.559
But this idea of buying
products and supporting products

00:20:43.559 --> 00:20:45.350
that have a positive
impact, whether that's

00:20:45.350 --> 00:20:47.880
on the environment, whether
that's on the community,

00:20:47.880 --> 00:20:51.660
I think now for millennials
and anyone that's under 30,

00:20:51.660 --> 00:20:55.460
I think that's a big part
of that purchase decision.

00:20:55.460 --> 00:20:59.560
Certainly as for me,
I'm not under 30.

00:20:59.560 --> 00:21:02.910
But I think if all
other things are equal,

00:21:02.910 --> 00:21:05.330
I'm willing to pay
a little bit more

00:21:05.330 --> 00:21:07.330
to know that this
product is having

00:21:07.330 --> 00:21:10.000
some sort of positive impact.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:12.460
At the end of the day, it still
has to be a strong product.

00:21:12.460 --> 00:21:14.290
So we learned it
even the hard way.

00:21:14.290 --> 00:21:16.370
We really put the mission
in front of the brand,

00:21:16.370 --> 00:21:18.750
and though of product second.

00:21:18.750 --> 00:21:21.210
And at Shinola, what I
really loved when I met them,

00:21:21.210 --> 00:21:22.170
I was like, wow.

00:21:22.170 --> 00:21:23.890
This product is amazing.

00:21:23.890 --> 00:21:26.780
The fact that we were
creating jobs to me

00:21:26.780 --> 00:21:27.840
was the cherry on top.

00:21:27.840 --> 00:21:30.020
But that product needs
to stand on its own.

00:21:30.020 --> 00:21:33.110
SPEAKER 1: Do you see that as
being increasingly challenging

00:21:33.110 --> 00:21:36.690
as the demand for the
product increases,

00:21:36.690 --> 00:21:38.410
and the scale and
the volume that you

00:21:38.410 --> 00:21:40.820
need to fulfill that
demand increases?

00:21:40.820 --> 00:21:44.240
As we think of other brands
who have maybe mentioned even

00:21:44.240 --> 00:21:45.260
Nike in this case.

00:21:45.260 --> 00:21:47.300
Do you see that as a
challenge for Shinola?

00:21:47.300 --> 00:21:48.841
BRIDGET RUSSO: It's
a huge challenge.

00:21:48.841 --> 00:21:52.530
You know, as you grow, and
we really look at everything

00:21:52.530 --> 00:21:55.450
we do from in the beginning,
we looked at where

00:21:55.450 --> 00:21:56.690
to source our shopping bags.

00:21:56.690 --> 00:21:58.960
And we said, well, we can
source them in the States

00:21:58.960 --> 00:22:00.880
and spend $12 on them.

00:22:00.880 --> 00:22:04.450
Or we could take the savings
of sourcing the bag overseas

00:22:04.450 --> 00:22:07.340
and put it towards R&amp;D to doing
what we're doing in Detroit

00:22:07.340 --> 00:22:08.920
and helping to grow that.

00:22:08.920 --> 00:22:11.440
And since then, we started
with the watch factory.

00:22:11.440 --> 00:22:15.812
I didn't mention, but we opened
a leather factory two years ago

00:22:15.812 --> 00:22:18.510
where we're producing the
majority of our leather watch

00:22:18.510 --> 00:22:20.690
straps and some of our
small leather goods.

00:22:20.690 --> 00:22:23.470
So again, continuing to
add to that capacity.

00:22:23.470 --> 00:22:26.650
The reality is, we're
in a global economy.

00:22:26.650 --> 00:22:29.370
So every single component
is not made under one roof.

00:22:29.370 --> 00:22:33.380
That hasn't existed
for a very long time.

00:22:33.380 --> 00:22:36.320
We felt very strongly
what we were doing-- we

00:22:36.320 --> 00:22:37.900
were doing more than assembly.

00:22:37.900 --> 00:22:39.910
And so we use the word "build."

00:22:39.910 --> 00:22:42.570
You guys probably read that's
got us into a little hot water

00:22:42.570 --> 00:22:43.110
recently.

00:22:43.110 --> 00:22:48.210
But I think it's an opportunity
for us to work with the FTC

00:22:48.210 --> 00:22:54.330
on clarifying for the consumer
and makers of products to say,

00:22:54.330 --> 00:22:55.330
this isn't clear.

00:22:55.330 --> 00:22:56.740
It's not clear for the consumer.

00:22:56.740 --> 00:22:59.180
And it's not clear
for anyone who's

00:22:59.180 --> 00:23:03.360
just trying to do business and
do the right thing in the US.

