00:34:47.553 --> 00:34:48.719
what the hell we're selling.

00:34:48.719 --> 00:34:49.880
But I'm intrigued.

00:34:49.880 --> 00:34:52.750
I want to know more about that
brand after seeing that video.

00:34:52.750 --> 00:34:54.650
So it is about the balance.

00:34:54.650 --> 00:34:55.719
It's about the mix.

00:34:55.719 --> 00:34:57.680
And don't be so
dictated by the data

00:34:57.680 --> 00:35:00.030
that you lose the fact that
you are all human beings

00:35:00.030 --> 00:35:01.810
and consumers as well.

00:35:01.810 --> 00:35:05.520
And that gut feeling of
what is right and taking

00:35:05.520 --> 00:35:07.000
some calculated risk.

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:08.340
SPEAKER 1: Yeah.

00:35:08.340 --> 00:35:10.190
I want to open it
up for any questions

00:35:10.190 --> 00:35:13.270
that you all might have that
you'd like to ask Bridget.

00:35:13.270 --> 00:35:14.069
Go ahead.

00:35:14.069 --> 00:35:14.610
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:35:14.610 --> 00:35:16.920
Thanks for coming in, first off.

00:35:16.920 --> 00:35:19.212
I did not know anything
about the association

00:35:19.212 --> 00:35:21.770
with the Schwinn family
to your bicycles.

00:35:21.770 --> 00:35:25.610
But that seems to be a model
in your brand extension.

00:35:25.610 --> 00:35:28.772
A personality or an expert
in the field to kind of

00:35:28.772 --> 00:35:30.002
help to launch that.

00:35:30.002 --> 00:35:31.970
Can you explain the
process of identifying

00:35:31.970 --> 00:35:34.437
that person that represents
best the Shinola brand,

00:35:34.437 --> 00:35:36.395
cause I would think it's
more art than science.

00:35:36.395 --> 00:35:40.060
Going back to the data, of
like, is it a relationship?

00:35:40.060 --> 00:35:43.180
How do you identify that
person that represents how

00:35:43.180 --> 00:35:45.019
you want to launch the brand?

00:35:45.019 --> 00:35:46.560
BRIDGET RUSSO: We've
been very lucky.

00:35:46.560 --> 00:35:49.660
Our founder knows
a lot of people.

00:35:49.660 --> 00:35:55.260
And so it's a little bit of
asking around, asking advice

00:35:55.260 --> 00:35:57.460
from friends.

00:35:57.460 --> 00:36:00.240
And then some people who
just somehow cross our paths

00:36:00.240 --> 00:36:03.490
because someone might know
what we're up to and say,

00:36:03.490 --> 00:36:04.960
I've got the person for you.

00:36:04.960 --> 00:36:07.120
You need to talk to
Sky Yaeger, or you

00:36:07.120 --> 00:36:08.510
need to talk to Alex Rossen.

00:36:08.510 --> 00:36:12.690
So it's been pretty organic
from that perspective.

00:36:12.690 --> 00:36:14.820
And we've never
done big searches.

00:36:14.820 --> 00:36:18.010
I mean, even we just
named Tom Lewand, our CEO,

00:36:18.010 --> 00:36:20.210
we didn't put the job out there.

00:36:20.210 --> 00:36:21.970
We never did.

00:36:21.970 --> 00:36:23.910
But we just start to
put our feelers out.

00:36:23.910 --> 00:36:26.050
Tom was working with us
on some side projects.

00:36:26.050 --> 00:36:29.030
And again, it was
that gut feeling

00:36:29.030 --> 00:36:32.450
that our founder felt like
this was the right guy

00:36:32.450 --> 00:36:34.240
to help lead the brand.

00:36:34.240 --> 00:36:36.150
And so that was
kind of, at least

00:36:36.150 --> 00:36:40.470
to date, how decisions are made
around people in particular.

00:36:40.470 --> 00:36:43.810
And it makes for a
really-- Tom, our founder,

00:36:43.810 --> 00:36:48.304
refers to us as the bar
scene in "Star Wars."

00:36:48.304 --> 00:36:50.480
And they took is as that.

00:36:50.480 --> 00:36:52.320
We all come from
varied backgrounds.

00:36:52.320 --> 00:36:54.940
But I think it's helpful
in keeping us on our toes,

00:36:54.940 --> 00:36:56.790
and also seeing
different perspectives.

00:36:56.790 --> 00:37:01.010
The fact that Tom comes
from the sports arena,

00:37:01.010 --> 00:37:02.780
and coming from that
background, I think

00:37:02.780 --> 00:37:05.586
is an interesting perspective
for-- we don't even

00:37:05.586 --> 00:37:07.210
like to call ourselves
a fashion brand.

00:37:07.210 --> 00:37:09.470
We see ourselves more
as a design brand.

00:37:09.470 --> 00:37:11.540
So I think having
those outside voices

00:37:11.540 --> 00:37:12.780
and that outside perspective.

00:37:12.780 --> 00:37:14.380
Because if you're all in
a room with the same--

00:37:14.380 --> 00:37:16.420
if we just had a whole
bunch of fashion people,

00:37:16.420 --> 00:37:20.147
we'd be doing things
very differently today.

00:37:20.147 --> 00:37:20.980
SPEAKER 1: Question.

00:37:20.980 --> 00:37:21.600
Go ahead.

00:37:21.600 --> 00:37:22.790
AUDIENCE: The sklil
trade has always

00:37:22.790 --> 00:37:24.255
been kind of a passion of mine.

00:37:24.255 --> 00:37:26.360
I grew up downriver
in [INAUDIBLE].

00:37:26.360 --> 00:37:28.942
In my parents'
generation had a shop.

00:37:28.942 --> 00:37:32.676
They had a actual working auto
shop within the high school

00:37:32.676 --> 00:37:33.300
and everything.

00:37:33.300 --> 00:37:37.660
And that generation was such
a stigma on [INAUDIBLE].

00:37:37.660 --> 00:37:40.660
How do you feel
especially with how deeply

00:37:40.660 --> 00:37:44.624
passionate people [INAUDIBLE]
upper middle that probably

00:37:44.624 --> 00:37:47.079
came from those families
that had the stigma.

00:37:47.079 --> 00:37:48.061
How do you do that?

00:37:48.061 --> 00:37:51.007
And where do you start
to try to remove it?

00:37:51.007 --> 00:37:52.480
Does it start with politicians?

00:37:52.480 --> 00:37:53.953
Does it start in schools?

00:37:53.953 --> 00:37:56.430
Does it start with the brand
advocates that you have?

00:37:56.430 --> 00:37:58.346
Recalibrating their
brand mindset?

00:37:58.346 --> 00:38:00.501
Where'd it really
start to get rid

00:38:00.501 --> 00:38:02.657
of that trade school
of underachieving,

00:38:02.657 --> 00:38:04.402
and you have to go to
a four-year school.

00:38:04.402 --> 00:38:06.652
Because those jobs aren't
gonna [INAUDIBLE] the skills

00:38:06.652 --> 00:38:09.007
do transcend and [INAUDIBLE].

00:38:09.007 --> 00:38:09.840
BRIDGET RUSSO: Yeah.

00:38:09.840 --> 00:38:13.510
I think definitely education
is one piece, and working

00:38:13.510 --> 00:38:15.050
at the civil level,
just make sure

00:38:15.050 --> 00:38:17.870
that you have the support
locally in these cities,

00:38:17.870 --> 00:38:20.170
because there are certain
cities like Detroit that

00:38:20.170 --> 00:38:27.480
are more better poised
to really drive this.

00:38:27.480 --> 00:38:30.790
Buffalo is another good city.

00:38:30.790 --> 00:38:35.240
And also working with
partners in the media who

00:38:35.240 --> 00:38:39.010
have such control now to really
shape people's opinions one

00:38:39.010 --> 00:38:42.860
way or the other, to
help tell the story.

00:38:42.860 --> 00:38:45.680
And you know, especially
now with things like Etsy,

00:38:45.680 --> 00:38:46.980
for instance.

00:38:46.980 --> 00:38:49.100
I think it's coming
back to where people

00:38:49.100 --> 00:38:52.490
are interested in learning how
to make things on their own,

00:38:52.490 --> 00:38:54.540
making things and selling them.

00:38:54.540 --> 00:38:58.590
Now with the great platform that
you can go direct to consumer.

00:38:58.590 --> 00:39:00.190
So it's good timing.

00:39:00.190 --> 00:39:02.090
And I think now
with kids coming out

00:39:02.090 --> 00:39:05.170
of college with that degree,
that really expensive degree,

00:39:05.170 --> 00:39:07.900
and no guarantee of a job, zero.

00:39:07.900 --> 00:39:08.440
You know.

00:39:08.440 --> 00:39:11.160
So people are looking
at different ways

00:39:11.160 --> 00:39:13.710
of how they can build a career.

00:39:13.710 --> 00:39:16.890
And it's not the
traditional doctor, lawyer.

00:39:16.890 --> 00:39:18.620
Not everyone can
be an entrepreneur

00:39:18.620 --> 00:39:20.760
and make the next
Uber or whatever.

00:39:20.760 --> 00:39:24.630
So education's a
big piece of it.

00:39:24.630 --> 00:39:31.150
But that you need that support
at the civil level to-- oh,

00:39:31.150 --> 00:39:32.910
what's the word?

00:39:32.910 --> 00:39:37.320
Making sure that there are
certain land agreements,

00:39:37.320 --> 00:39:40.590
that it's not just about
building luxury condos.

00:39:40.590 --> 00:39:42.380
Because it's very
quick to say a factory

00:39:42.380 --> 00:39:47.540
will not yield as much from
a real estate perspective

00:39:47.540 --> 00:39:48.570
than a luxury condo.

00:39:48.570 --> 00:39:51.980
But you know, that's not going
to help build a community.

00:39:51.980 --> 00:39:57.200
And certainly not help build
diversity within the community.

00:39:57.200 --> 00:39:59.350
And I'm hoping Detroit
has an opportunity.

00:39:59.350 --> 00:40:02.940
And there's a lot of
people working hard at this

00:40:02.940 --> 00:40:06.220
to help build this
infrastructure.

00:40:06.220 --> 00:40:08.770
And also, if we can
make it work in Detroit,

00:40:08.770 --> 00:40:12.030
that's the blueprint, let's
hope, to do it in other cities.

00:40:12.030 --> 00:40:14.620
But I was one of those kids
who grew up in the factory.

00:40:14.620 --> 00:40:16.770
And I said from
a very young age,

00:40:16.770 --> 00:40:19.060
I would never work
in the factory.

00:40:19.060 --> 00:40:22.050
My brothers, on the other
hand, did work in the factory.

00:40:22.050 --> 00:40:25.740
Made a lot more
money than I did.

00:40:25.740 --> 00:40:30.090
Got burned when things
by the '90s, that was it.

00:40:30.090 --> 00:40:31.430
But it's all coming back now.

00:40:31.430 --> 00:40:33.390
My brother actually
held on to his machines.

00:40:33.390 --> 00:40:36.560
And now his knitting
business, he's

00:40:36.560 --> 00:40:39.117
getting the phone calls
that-- a lot of people

00:40:39.117 --> 00:40:39.950
sold their machines.

00:40:39.950 --> 00:40:42.260
He happened to hold on.

00:40:42.260 --> 00:40:44.167
But I think there's a
huge opportunity there.

00:40:44.167 --> 00:40:46.500
But it's going to be a lot
of different entities working

00:40:46.500 --> 00:40:47.010
together.

00:40:47.010 --> 00:40:48.950
And there needs to
be a huge PR campaign

00:40:48.950 --> 00:40:53.440
that the media can help drive
to change the perception.

00:40:53.440 --> 00:40:55.190
SPEAKER 1: So a lot
of people in this room

00:40:55.190 --> 00:40:57.310
work with CMOs every day.

00:40:57.310 --> 00:41:02.920
They have to go and meet
and provide thoughts, ideas.

00:41:02.920 --> 00:41:04.420
Sitting there-- and
obviously you've

00:41:04.420 --> 00:41:05.790
had a good PR background.

00:41:05.790 --> 00:41:07.690
It's helped set you
up for a lot of things

00:41:07.690 --> 00:41:09.060
you're even handling today.

00:41:09.060 --> 00:41:10.560
Could you give them advice?

00:41:10.560 --> 00:41:12.730
And how do you think
about when people

00:41:12.730 --> 00:41:15.890
come in-- you said you
talked to your agency

00:41:15.890 --> 00:41:18.794
about the ad that was going to
run when the Apple Watch was

00:41:18.794 --> 00:41:19.460
being announced.

00:41:19.460 --> 00:41:23.390
Can you give us any advice
for how you think about it?

00:41:23.390 --> 00:41:26.240
Or when someone comes in to
talk with you about ideas

00:41:26.240 --> 00:41:28.665
or thoughts, how you
think about things?

00:41:28.665 --> 00:41:30.040
BRIDGET RUSSO:
For me, I'm always

00:41:30.040 --> 00:41:33.790
impressed when someone takes
the time to research your brand.

00:41:33.790 --> 00:41:36.290
All the information's
out there now.

00:41:36.290 --> 00:41:38.050
Not all of it accurate.

00:41:38.050 --> 00:41:41.350
But there is a lot
of sources out there

00:41:41.350 --> 00:41:43.790
where you can really educate
yourself about a brand.

00:41:43.790 --> 00:41:47.340
I mean, even for people
who are interviewing.

00:41:47.340 --> 00:41:50.320
I'm often shocked by people who
don't really do their research.

00:41:50.320 --> 00:41:52.960
I went, why are you here?

00:41:52.960 --> 00:41:54.370
So do your research.

00:41:54.370 --> 00:41:57.410
Help them realize
that you took a moment

00:41:57.410 --> 00:41:58.890
to not only understand
their brand,

00:41:58.890 --> 00:42:00.265
but to understand
their business.

00:42:00.265 --> 00:42:03.600
So not only researching
Shinola, but looking

00:42:03.600 --> 00:42:08.371
at where we sit in Nordstrom
and who's our competitive set,

00:42:08.371 --> 00:42:10.620
and looking at their business
leading up to a meeting.

00:42:10.620 --> 00:42:13.160
You don't need to
become a watch expert.

00:42:13.160 --> 00:42:15.920
But just gathering
that information

00:42:15.920 --> 00:42:17.896
and bringing that to
the meeting to say,

00:42:17.896 --> 00:42:19.020
we looked at your business.

00:42:19.020 --> 00:42:20.680
We looked at your
competitive set.

00:42:20.680 --> 00:42:22.264
And here's some
learnings that we had

00:42:22.264 --> 00:42:23.430
from an outside perspective.

00:42:23.430 --> 00:42:25.640
Because often you guys
might see something

00:42:25.640 --> 00:42:28.580
that we don't see because
we're in the thick of it.

00:42:28.580 --> 00:42:32.064
So I think a fresh approach
to just the information

00:42:32.064 --> 00:42:34.230
that's out there before you
even get to the meeting.

00:42:34.230 --> 00:42:34.440
SPEAKER 1: Yeah.

00:42:34.440 --> 00:42:35.490
You had a question.

00:42:35.490 --> 00:42:37.470
Go ahead.

00:42:37.470 --> 00:42:40.935
AUDIENCE: We all know Detroit is
world-famous for manufacturing.

00:42:40.935 --> 00:42:42.420
You talked about that.

00:42:42.420 --> 00:42:44.895
But also famous for creativity.

00:42:44.895 --> 00:42:51.330
And I wondered if you could
speak a little bit to Detroit's

00:42:51.330 --> 00:42:53.805
influence on Shinola designs.

00:42:53.805 --> 00:42:56.775
[INAUDIBLE] the
future, especially

00:42:56.775 --> 00:43:01.972
with some of these world-class
leaders in the new areas

00:43:01.972 --> 00:43:06.180
you're going into being New
York based, as you might expect.

00:43:06.180 --> 00:43:09.645
But how is Detroit
perhaps playing the role

00:43:09.645 --> 00:43:11.925
of [INAUDIBLE]?

00:43:11.925 --> 00:43:13.300
BRIDGET RUSSO:
For us, we're very

00:43:13.300 --> 00:43:17.270
from a product perspective,
inspired by the architecture.

00:43:17.270 --> 00:43:19.820
So definitely the
architecture of Detroit.

00:43:19.820 --> 00:43:22.810
I would say the spirit and
the attitude of Detroit

00:43:22.810 --> 00:43:24.000
you see in our marketing.

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:28.650
And sort of the irreverence of
our voice comes from Detroit.

00:43:28.650 --> 00:43:34.560
That Detroit versus
everybody sort of sentiment.

00:43:34.560 --> 00:43:40.240
You know, I do think that in
order for Detroit to really

00:43:40.240 --> 00:43:43.580
be a player as it was in
the global marketplace

00:43:43.580 --> 00:43:46.300
from a creativity
innovation standpoint,

00:43:46.300 --> 00:43:50.320
it needs to be a place
that maintains its talent,

00:43:50.320 --> 00:43:52.660
because often what happens
is the talent's here.

00:43:52.660 --> 00:43:53.740
And they leave.

00:43:53.740 --> 00:43:54.590
They go to Chicago.

00:43:54.590 --> 00:43:57.070
They go to New York, because
the opportunity isn't here.

00:43:57.070 --> 00:44:02.220
So as businesses continue
to grow or move to Detroit,

00:44:02.220 --> 00:44:05.340
I think that's an
opportunity to get back

00:44:05.340 --> 00:44:08.810
in the ranks, if you will,
of being an innovative city,

00:44:08.810 --> 00:44:12.610
of being a city that
drives creative.

00:44:12.610 --> 00:44:15.990
It certainly inspires
us every day.

00:44:15.990 --> 00:44:18.620
But I think being able
to keep the talent that

00:44:18.620 --> 00:44:21.734
comes here is something
that we need to work on.

00:44:21.734 --> 00:44:23.900
I mean, the education system
is a whole other thing,

00:44:23.900 --> 00:44:27.790
because if you're a young person
or if you're coming married

00:44:27.790 --> 00:44:29.535
with kids, I don't have kids.

00:44:29.535 --> 00:44:30.410
So I live in Detroit.

00:44:30.410 --> 00:44:33.450
I'm not worried about the
education system personally.

00:44:33.450 --> 00:44:36.970
But it's a huge
problem, because I

00:44:36.970 --> 00:44:38.680
have colleagues
of mine that say I

00:44:38.680 --> 00:44:39.930
would love to live in Detroit.

00:44:39.930 --> 00:44:41.971
But I don't know where to
send my kids to school.

00:44:41.971 --> 00:44:44.080
So they'd drive them to
Grosse Point or whatever.

00:44:44.080 --> 00:44:45.830
After a while-- first
of all, not everyone

00:44:45.830 --> 00:44:48.250
has access to do that.

00:44:48.250 --> 00:44:51.040
So those are things that
are really important.

00:44:51.040 --> 00:44:52.660
Just basic things.

00:44:52.660 --> 00:44:55.750
Our public school system
really needs a lot of work

00:44:55.750 --> 00:44:57.450
in order to make this
an attractive city

00:44:57.450 --> 00:44:59.890
for creative people, for
business-minded people

00:44:59.890 --> 00:45:02.260
to live in, and build
a family, and not

00:45:02.260 --> 00:45:04.260
have to go live in the
suburbs because they need

00:45:04.260 --> 00:45:06.850
to be in a certain zip
code for their kids

00:45:06.850 --> 00:45:07.820
to go to a good school.

00:45:07.820 --> 00:45:08.486
SPEAKER 1: Yeah.

00:45:08.486 --> 00:45:10.290
Very important.

00:45:10.290 --> 00:45:10.840
I'll

00:45:10.840 --> 00:45:12.533
One last question
from the audience.

00:45:12.533 --> 00:45:14.301
And I'll close with one.

00:45:14.301 --> 00:45:14.800
Go ahead.

00:45:14.800 --> 00:45:18.720
AUDIENCE: So this may be a
little bit of [INAUDIBLE] here.

00:45:18.720 --> 00:45:21.270
When Shinola was
started, to what extent

00:45:21.270 --> 00:45:23.910
was Detroit factored in
as the only location?

00:45:23.910 --> 00:45:27.834
Or was it like, one of several
locations that were considered?

00:45:27.834 --> 00:45:29.720
I've heard how price
point was factored

00:45:29.720 --> 00:45:31.872
into choosing Detroit
as a potential location

00:45:31.872 --> 00:45:32.830
to headquarter Shinola.

00:45:32.830 --> 00:45:34.884
And then part two of that.

00:45:34.884 --> 00:45:36.462
As you expand
internationally, what

00:45:36.462 --> 00:45:39.236
is the recognition of Detroit
on the international level?

00:45:39.236 --> 00:45:41.354
And do you think that
Shinola itself is now

00:45:41.354 --> 00:45:43.520
going to become the vehicle
to help promote Detroit?

00:45:43.520 --> 00:45:45.600
Rather than Detroit
promoted Shinola,

00:45:45.600 --> 00:45:48.250
it almost seems like
it's now Shinola's turn

00:45:48.250 --> 00:45:50.137
to promote Detroit [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:50.137 --> 00:45:52.220
BRIDGET RUSSO: Well, we
definitely are doing that.

00:45:52.220 --> 00:45:55.070
I mean, this brand,
part of our DNA,

00:45:55.070 --> 00:45:58.710
what we built this brand on is
the fact that we're in Detroit,

00:45:58.710 --> 00:46:01.610
the fact that we
have a watch factory

00:46:01.610 --> 00:46:03.650
and a leather
factory in Detroit.

00:46:03.650 --> 00:46:06.560
The intention was always that
this would be a global brand.

00:46:06.560 --> 00:46:11.320
We didn't know how
the Detroit name would

00:46:11.320 --> 00:46:15.190
resonate certainly outside
of Michigan, but even outside

00:46:15.190 --> 00:46:15.840
of the US.

00:46:15.840 --> 00:46:20.440
What we're finding is people--
it's resonating because it's

00:46:20.440 --> 00:46:21.550
that underdog story.

00:46:21.550 --> 00:46:23.128
People want Detroit to win.

00:46:26.060 --> 00:46:27.284
There's a Detroit everywhere.

00:46:33.250 --> 00:46:36.880
So, sorry.

00:46:36.880 --> 00:46:38.605
It is resonating.

00:46:38.605 --> 00:46:39.752
And I'm choking.

00:46:39.752 --> 00:46:41.440
SPEAKER 1: No, don't
choke, don't choke.

00:46:41.440 --> 00:46:41.939
It's funny.

00:46:41.939 --> 00:46:44.520
Cause I think as we
travel, many of us

00:46:44.520 --> 00:46:46.010
travel all over the place.

00:46:46.010 --> 00:46:49.100
And we probably all feel that
we're the ones standing up

00:46:49.100 --> 00:46:49.880
for Detroit.

00:46:49.880 --> 00:46:54.990
I know whether I'm here
or internationally, I

00:46:54.990 --> 00:46:55.840
get teased a lot.

00:46:55.840 --> 00:46:56.580
Oh, Detroit.

00:46:56.580 --> 00:46:57.500
What's happening in Detroit?

00:46:57.500 --> 00:46:58.416
And I'm like, come on.

00:46:58.416 --> 00:46:59.160
Detroit's great.

00:46:59.160 --> 00:47:02.940
So I feel like we're all
feel that a lot of time.

00:47:02.940 --> 00:47:05.170
BRIDGET RUSSO: But to
answer the price question.

00:47:05.170 --> 00:47:06.472
It wasn't really so much price.

00:47:06.472 --> 00:47:08.680
Cause we invested a lot of
money to build the factory

00:47:08.680 --> 00:47:12.030
and do the training,
which we continue to do.

00:47:12.030 --> 00:47:14.220
And we did not take
the tax incentives

00:47:14.220 --> 00:47:16.240
that were offered to us.

00:47:16.240 --> 00:47:18.910
Certainly it's cheaper to
open a factory in Detroit

00:47:18.910 --> 00:47:22.490
than it is in the middle
of Manhattan or LA.

00:47:22.490 --> 00:47:26.300
But really the
opportunity that we saw,

00:47:26.300 --> 00:47:29.970
you had a workforce, a
trained and talented workforce

00:47:29.970 --> 00:47:31.427
that were sitting without jobs.

00:47:31.427 --> 00:47:33.885
So we thought we could transfer
that skill into watchmaking

00:47:33.885 --> 00:47:36.250
and leather making.

00:47:36.250 --> 00:47:37.660
So sure.

00:47:37.660 --> 00:47:39.452
Is it cheaper to open
a factory in Detroit?

00:47:39.452 --> 00:47:39.951
Yes.

00:47:39.951 --> 00:47:42.500
I mean, that's changing now
with real estate booming the way

00:47:42.500 --> 00:47:45.130
that it's doing.

00:47:45.130 --> 00:47:47.730
But it wasn't necessarily
about the price.

00:47:47.730 --> 00:47:51.232
It was about the opportunity
and the talent base that

00:47:51.232 --> 00:47:52.440
exists here in manufacturing.

